[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah, hey, this is Dan.

195
00:15:39,203 --> 00:15:49,230
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm kind of, things are a bit difficult for me to take on too much responsibility right now, but I am happy to like a co-chair kind of thing.

196
00:15:49,250 --> 00:15:55,455
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, to make sure there's some Medford representation as well.

197
00:15:56,235 --> 00:16:03,921
[SPEAKER_02]: I don't think it's like too prohibitive, but yeah, Sarah, if you want to do like a chair, co-chair, I'm perfectly happy to do that.

198
00:16:04,987 --> 00:16:07,848
[SPEAKER_00]: I think the co-chair arrangement sounds even better.

199
00:16:07,868 --> 00:16:15,992
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd be more comfortable with that because I still need to learn the protocol terminology and I think co-chair sounds perfect.

200
00:16:17,613 --> 00:16:22,415
[SPEAKER_03]: Plus if you're ever like out of town or something, you'd like to have a co-chair to step in.

201
00:16:22,435 --> 00:16:29,299
[SPEAKER_03]: All right, so we have Dan and Sarah and anybody else that would express an interest?

202
00:16:30,219 --> 00:16:34,181
[SPEAKER_01]: I would certainly be remiss not to throw my metaphorical hat in the ring.

203
00:16:37,093 --> 00:16:47,075
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, what we'll do next month is each of you can speak to this a little more formally, and then we'll, we might, I don't know if we can have three co-chairs.

204
00:16:47,115 --> 00:16:54,336
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, it's possible if we have like 10 meeting or 10 or 11 meetings a year, so you could rotate.

205
00:16:54,356 --> 00:16:56,996
[SPEAKER_04]: They should, Bob, you shouldn't decide for them.

206
00:16:57,577 --> 00:16:59,077
[SPEAKER_04]: Let them talk to each other.

207
00:16:59,097 --> 00:16:59,577
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

208
00:16:59,797 --> 00:17:00,697
[SPEAKER_04]: Very good.

209
00:17:00,737 --> 00:17:02,597
[SPEAKER_04]: Discuss and let the committee vote.

210
00:17:02,717 --> 00:17:04,038
[SPEAKER_04]: Don't try to solve it for them.

211
00:17:04,718 --> 00:17:05,038
[SPEAKER_03]: All right.

212
00:17:05,238 --> 00:17:05,598
[SPEAKER_03]: Very good.

213
00:17:08,271 --> 00:17:09,472
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you for your interest.

214
00:17:11,594 --> 00:17:13,836
[SPEAKER_03]: Did I miss anyone who would be interested?

215
00:17:14,896 --> 00:17:16,878
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, we'll take it up next month.

216
00:17:17,579 --> 00:17:35,193
[SPEAKER_03]: There's also the issue of members should just make sure that they're reaffirming their intent to remain on the committee for the next year that we usually have everyone just reaffirm their commitment to serve for the next calendar year.

217
00:17:37,411 --> 00:17:41,555
[SPEAKER_03]: Sometimes we get people who decide to leave the committee at that point.

218
00:17:42,476 --> 00:17:48,682
[SPEAKER_04]: If I might clarify, and a lot of boards and commissions, you're appointed for a specific term, and at the end of your term.

219
00:17:49,213 --> 00:17:51,634
[SPEAKER_04]: then we kind of say, do you want to be reappointed?

220
00:17:52,374 --> 00:17:56,676
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's an easy like point because this committee is ad hoc.

221
00:17:56,736 --> 00:17:57,817
[SPEAKER_04]: There are not terms.

222
00:17:59,137 --> 00:18:10,022
[SPEAKER_04]: So it is useful for people to actually, we would much rather have somebody say, I'm sorry, I don't have time for this in my life and step down, then just stop attending meetings.

223
00:18:10,102 --> 00:18:12,343
[SPEAKER_04]: And then we have trouble making quorum.

224
00:18:12,883 --> 00:18:15,724
[SPEAKER_04]: So we want people to like say, no, I have time.

225
00:18:16,184 --> 00:18:17,365
[SPEAKER_04]: I will continue to come.

226
00:18:17,785 --> 00:18:20,488
[SPEAKER_04]: so that they don't, and you don't have to email us or anything.

227
00:18:20,508 --> 00:18:26,613
[SPEAKER_04]: It's just, if you realize that you don't have time, you know, let us know.

228
00:18:28,275 --> 00:18:32,079
[SPEAKER_03]: Just making sure I haven't missed any members that have joined since we started this.

229
00:18:32,239 --> 00:18:33,140
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think so.

230
00:18:34,781 --> 00:18:37,824
[SPEAKER_07]: Can I ask an off the agenda question?

231
00:18:37,844 --> 00:18:39,486
[SPEAKER_07]: Go ahead.

232
00:18:40,346 --> 00:18:41,808
[SPEAKER_07]: Sarah, what will you be doing?

233
00:18:43,995 --> 00:18:45,756
[SPEAKER_00]: Oh, thanks for asking, Lois.

234
00:18:46,397 --> 00:18:47,617
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, I'm excited to tell you all.

235
00:18:48,138 --> 00:18:49,338
[SPEAKER_00]: It's actually very relevant.

236
00:18:50,599 --> 00:18:54,582
[SPEAKER_00]: So I accepted a job offer with the Nashua River Watershed Association.

237
00:18:55,282 --> 00:18:58,844
[SPEAKER_00]: My job is conservation and climate resilience specialist.

238
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:04,888
[SPEAKER_00]: And they have made me the project manager for the MVP NBS grant.

239
00:19:05,529 --> 00:19:11,873
[SPEAKER_00]: So this is a $400,000 grant that is for nature-based solutions in five communities.

240
00:19:12,733 --> 00:19:16,534
[SPEAKER_00]: in the Groton, Fitchburg, Nashua River area.

241
00:19:17,234 --> 00:19:24,117
[SPEAKER_00]: So now I'm talking to these communities, their DPW, the Conservation Commission, environmental committees.

242
00:19:24,817 --> 00:19:33,920
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'm learning a lot about what communities across Massachusetts are doing for climate resilience, for dealing with flooding.

243
00:19:34,900 --> 00:19:37,281
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'd love to report back to you all what I'm learning.

244
00:19:37,301 --> 00:19:41,242
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

245
00:19:43,495 --> 00:19:44,436
[SPEAKER_03]: Congratulations.

246
00:19:46,318 --> 00:19:48,340
[SPEAKER_03]: I think that's all for organizational items.

247
00:19:49,862 --> 00:19:55,989
[SPEAKER_03]: I have not seen anyone from the Tufts energy group drawing, so we'll skip that part of the administrative.

248
00:19:56,930 --> 00:20:00,033
[SPEAKER_03]: Aspects that were just about at the end of that.

249
00:20:00,874 --> 00:20:03,737
[SPEAKER_03]: Time slot anyway, now let's review.

250
00:20:04,947 --> 00:20:14,549
[SPEAKER_03]: The 23rd, 2023 harvester energy festival for any reaction comments notes for next year, et cetera.

251
00:20:14,689 --> 00:20:20,210
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'll let Loretta lead that discussion, but we can all join in many, many of us.

252
00:20:21,690 --> 00:20:23,071
[SPEAKER_03]: We're we're there.

253
00:20:23,091 --> 00:20:29,312
