279
00:22:14,981 --> 00:22:21,943
[SPEAKER_10]: So when he's feeling better, really sick, they'll get back to me with their numbers of what they collected.

280
00:22:29,285 --> 00:22:33,687
[SPEAKER_03]: Other comments from people who thought there could have been something done better.

281
00:22:40,745 --> 00:22:46,873
[SPEAKER_09]: Is there any way that we can reduce the amount of stuff that people walk away with?

282
00:22:47,634 --> 00:22:58,346
[SPEAKER_09]: The giant bag of, pardon my language, stuff that my son came home with from each of the tables.

283
00:22:59,287 --> 00:23:06,931
[SPEAKER_09]: I kind of, he walked, granted he walked in, he was incredibly excited of all the exciting things that he brought home from each table.

284
00:23:07,631 --> 00:23:14,794
[SPEAKER_09]: And I kind of looked at him and I was like, wait, this is kind of the opposite of what I think we're trying to stand for.

285
00:23:14,814 --> 00:23:26,880
[SPEAKER_09]: As he's like unpacking stickers and papers and this, and I understand that it's marketing and it's tools for education and things like that, but some of it,

286
00:23:28,057 --> 00:23:39,965
[SPEAKER_09]: I don't know if there's a way to work with vendors and tables and things like that in the future, but I have now a giant bag from the festival full of stuff.

287
00:23:40,745 --> 00:23:47,690
[SPEAKER_09]: And I'm sure many people do too, that, you know, maybe one item per vendor table.

288
00:23:49,711 --> 00:23:50,191
[SPEAKER_10]: Interesting.

289
00:23:51,052 --> 00:23:52,113
[SPEAKER_07]: Just a thought.

290
00:23:54,027 --> 00:23:57,348
[SPEAKER_07]: And you didn't even see all the candy that he already ate, right?

291
00:23:57,949 --> 00:24:00,630
[SPEAKER_09]: Oh, I'm sure he had so much candy in him.

292
00:24:01,070 --> 00:24:02,511
[SPEAKER_09]: He was there for the long haul.

293
00:24:02,591 --> 00:24:05,432
[SPEAKER_09]: So, I mean, it was like, you know, an eight year old's dream.

294
00:24:06,292 --> 00:24:13,355
[SPEAKER_09]: A bag of like five million stickers and pencils and balls and Lord knows what else, but.

295
00:24:20,831 --> 00:24:22,272
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I would like to second that.

296
00:24:22,532 --> 00:24:31,579
[SPEAKER_01]: Maybe there are ways to encourage different kinds of giving and different kinds of materials that could be given out.

297
00:24:33,401 --> 00:24:47,652
[SPEAKER_01]: I think of the folks that are giving out tree saplings and things that are either biodegradable or already kind of designed to be, I don't know, not saved and are not just marketing junk.

298
00:24:49,097 --> 00:24:54,699
[SPEAKER_09]: And I mean, I get the need for, I 100% understand the need for the marketing.

299
00:24:55,199 --> 00:25:01,200
[SPEAKER_09]: And I know that people go to these events with the hopes of marketing and the hopes that someone brings home something that has their name on it.

300
00:25:01,720 --> 00:25:08,102
[SPEAKER_09]: But like, I think, you know, waste management sent him home with like 10 different items.

301
00:25:10,163 --> 00:25:12,083
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, he has pencils from them.

302
00:25:12,103 --> 00:25:13,884
[SPEAKER_09]: He has a Frisbee from them.

303
00:25:13,904 --> 00:25:15,564
[SPEAKER_09]: He has a ball from them.

304
00:25:15,864 --> 00:25:17,385
[SPEAKER_09]: I mean, wow.

305
00:25:21,426 --> 00:25:22,806
[SPEAKER_03]: Business for waste management.

306
00:25:23,526 --> 00:25:26,447
[SPEAKER_09]: Yeah, I know that that's the higher name about that one.

307
00:25:26,907 --> 00:25:34,170
[SPEAKER_09]: But so it's like maybe trying to say, hey, can you bring one marketing thing to your table?

308
00:25:36,150 --> 00:25:37,331
[SPEAKER_10]: Hmm, interesting.

309
00:25:37,931 --> 00:25:43,032
[SPEAKER_10]: Or maybe they can, I'm not sure, but QR code posters to get the information.

310
00:25:43,072 --> 00:25:45,113
[SPEAKER_10]: But I don't know, they like to give out stuff, so.

311
00:25:46,322 --> 00:26:00,716
[SPEAKER_09]: And I completely, I get it that, you know, that people love collecting things, my son included, but you know, just a thought at an event like that, maybe we could try and curb it a little bit.

312
00:26:02,077 --> 00:26:06,601
[SPEAKER_05]: Or maybe ask them to not bring plastic products.

313
00:26:06,922 --> 00:26:07,963
[SPEAKER_09]: That would be something.

314
00:26:08,523 --> 00:26:09,304
[SPEAKER_09]: That'd be a start.

315
00:26:14,047 --> 00:26:22,674
[SPEAKER_07]: I'd like to tell Will that those trees that Trees Medford was giving away were to be planted.

316
00:26:23,594 --> 00:26:24,995
[SPEAKER_07]: We weren't giving them away.

317
00:26:26,116 --> 00:26:35,262
[SPEAKER_07]: People had to express an interest, assure us that they had where to plant them, take the instructions and go.

318
00:26:35,743 --> 00:26:40,186
[SPEAKER_07]: It was not a blind giveaway by any means.

319
00:26:42,062 --> 00:26:46,344
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I found that to be a far more meaningful and impactful way to engage with the table.

320
00:26:47,705 --> 00:26:48,505
[SPEAKER_01]: So I appreciated it.

321
00:26:49,645 --> 00:26:54,968
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, I thought you were saying that people were even giving away saplings.

322
00:26:58,321 --> 00:27:18,482
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, you know, I can talk about a few things about the festival that I observed and I had suggested that we do the same thing next year with three recycling events that, you know, we picked the date earlier and maybe give the electronics recycling in a separate, um, parking area.

323
00:27:19,103 --> 00:27:20,845
[SPEAKER_10]: Uh, the line did get backed up.

324
00:27:21,815 --> 00:27:31,683
[SPEAKER_10]: In my notes, if you read the notes that I sent out, some people were waiting 40, 45 minutes in line up past the Andrews School and they couldn't get by.

325
00:27:31,723 --> 00:27:37,608
[SPEAKER_10]: So they made, some people were making U-turns because they go down that road to cut through to other areas.

326
00:27:37,728 --> 00:27:42,812
[SPEAKER_10]: So, you know, that's more of a design thing for next year to keep in mind.

327
00:27:43,792 --> 00:27:48,396
[SPEAKER_10]: Picking the date earlier so that we could, if Alicia agrees.

328
00:27:50,312 --> 00:27:54,175
[SPEAKER_10]: so that we can try to reserve those three parking lots just for the festival.

329
00:27:56,796 --> 00:28:04,861
[SPEAKER_10]: And it really wasn't something that we were aware of, maybe.

330
00:28:05,681 --> 00:28:10,464
[SPEAKER_10]: I was told by some of the people that they were waiting in line and actually saw her at one point.

331
00:28:11,385 --> 00:28:18,049
[SPEAKER_10]: And so the way it was just too much for one little parking lot.

332
00:28:18,069 --> 00:28:19,630
[SPEAKER_10]: And the beer garden,

333
00:28:20,645 --> 00:28:26,846
[SPEAKER_10]: And the food vendor there, it didn't work out exactly as planned, but that was no fault of our own.

334
00:28:27,326 --> 00:28:33,948
[SPEAKER_10]: I thought the Beard Garden could have done much better if they brought their own tent, but they came as one.

335
00:28:34,028 --> 00:28:36,748
[SPEAKER_10]: So that was very confusing when they showed up.

336
00:28:37,449 --> 00:28:43,890
[SPEAKER_10]: So they came with Scott Brothers Meats, and there were several people that didn't realize

337
00:28:44,530 --> 00:28:47,072
[SPEAKER_10]: that the alcohol was behind there.

338
00:28:47,473 --> 00:28:52,457
[SPEAKER_10]: So next year, if we do the beer garden, we can do better with that.

339
00:28:53,958 --> 00:28:57,041
[SPEAKER_10]: But Chicken and Rice guys reported they did really well.

340
00:28:58,322 --> 00:28:59,563
[SPEAKER_10]: So I was happy for that.

341
00:29:00,324 --> 00:29:05,529
[SPEAKER_10]: And as far as exhibit, we do send out exhibitor feedback forms and we got some back.

342
00:29:06,189 --> 00:29:09,052
[SPEAKER_10]: And it was interesting because we changed the raffle.

343
00:29:10,487 --> 00:29:11,448
[SPEAKER_10]: in the way it was handled.

344
00:29:11,908 --> 00:29:13,089
[SPEAKER_10]: And some people liked it.

345
00:29:13,709 --> 00:29:18,032
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, they said it wasn't clear how the raffle tickets and what the purpose was.

346
00:29:18,633 --> 00:29:22,235
[SPEAKER_10]: And those were sent from some vendors that didn't have a raffle item.

347
00:29:22,856 --> 00:29:29,620
[SPEAKER_10]: So I looked back and I thought, okay, so if I was an attendee and I was an exhibitor, how would that feel?

348
00:29:29,680 --> 00:29:30,881
[SPEAKER_10]: And I could understand that.

349
00:29:31,501 --> 00:29:34,644
[SPEAKER_10]: So maybe next year we hand out the raffle tickets.

350
00:29:35,384 --> 00:29:39,927
[SPEAKER_10]: to the exhibitors that have a raffle instead of to all attendees.

351
00:29:40,548 --> 00:29:46,892
[SPEAKER_10]: So what would happen is people would have their raffle tickets and go up to tables and go do a raffle.

352
00:29:47,592 --> 00:29:50,995
[SPEAKER_10]: And some of the exhibitors didn't have a raffle and they weren't sure what to do with that.

353
00:29:52,095 --> 00:30:03,463
[SPEAKER_10]: So and a couple of exhibitors liked it the old way, where we had one table with all the raffle items on that table.

354
00:30:04,208 --> 00:30:12,031
[SPEAKER_10]: But we had learned from the past that some, some attendees just come and stand at that table and don't visit the exhibitors.

355
00:30:12,091 --> 00:30:13,311
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's why we changed it.

356
00:30:13,551 --> 00:30:17,533
[SPEAKER_10]: Plus also the amount of staff needed to me in that table.

357
00:30:20,474 --> 00:30:22,095
[SPEAKER_03]: Oh, Dan, you have your hand up.

358
00:30:28,057 --> 00:30:28,337
[SPEAKER_02]: Yeah.

359
00:30:28,777 --> 00:30:33,559
[SPEAKER_02]: And sorry for the background noise, uh, driving back up to Boston right now, but, um,

360
00:30:35,353 --> 00:30:47,679
[SPEAKER_02]: I've got two kids who play Medford soccer, and they're in the same, like, fields right there at the same time as the Harvester Energy Festival, and I know there's football over at the other field right there.

361
00:30:48,059 --> 00:30:58,264
[SPEAKER_02]: One thing I'd like to suggest, I asked a lot of our friends if they got a chance to walk over and check out the festival, and they said that they didn't even know it was going on.

362
00:30:59,665 --> 00:31:02,827
[SPEAKER_02]: I'd love to suggest and also just volunteer to

363
00:31:03,678 --> 00:31:13,024
[SPEAKER_02]: you know, maybe reach out through some of those youth sports groups that are using all the fields and the area over there next year or for other events as well.

364
00:31:13,244 --> 00:31:16,546
[SPEAKER_02]: I think you'd get a ton of people going over.

365
00:31:17,867 --> 00:31:20,028
[SPEAKER_02]: Just a quick suggestion.

366
00:31:20,868 --> 00:31:31,255
[SPEAKER_02]: Also, I was just thinking while we were talking about, you know, like reach out and then ways of, you know, that people are giving out things.

367
00:31:32,187 --> 00:31:57,747
[SPEAKER_02]: One thing I really liked while we were trick-or-treating this year, I got about three or four different people mentioning the Mothers Out Front Pumpkin Smash event coming up and offering like very small little outreach for that or just saying, you know, go to this next weekend, which I thought after hearing them talk here was really cool and really interesting and a great way just to make that known in the community.

368
00:32:00,402 --> 00:32:05,587
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, they were an exhibitor at the festival.

369
00:32:05,607 --> 00:32:09,410
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that what you mean?

