[SPEAKER_03]: And if you and Lois are willing to take input from some of us.

822
01:15:01,039 --> 01:15:01,820
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, I can do that.

823
01:15:02,223 --> 01:15:07,165
[SPEAKER_03]: And then report back a distilled set of comments, that'd be good.

824
01:15:09,927 --> 01:15:15,089
[SPEAKER_03]: So I guess you all have the, I sent out the, especially the private one.

825
01:15:15,109 --> 01:15:26,814
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the, although there might be some comments on the public tree and the tree committee, but I think the private one is the most different than before.

826
01:15:28,675 --> 01:15:29,876
[SPEAKER_03]: In my view, it was,

827
01:15:32,002 --> 01:15:37,123
[SPEAKER_03]: There was no mention of anything about the diameter of breast height at all.

828
01:15:37,583 --> 01:15:45,645
[SPEAKER_03]: There's no quantification because before it was like $300 per inch and there's nothing about that in there.

829
01:15:46,625 --> 01:15:47,685
[SPEAKER_10]: In the draft, right.

830
01:15:47,805 --> 01:15:52,926
[SPEAKER_03]: And then there was about, if you clear a lot, you only have to pay $1,000 for the clearing a hole.

831
01:15:53,086 --> 01:15:55,207
[SPEAKER_03]: That was like, holy mackerel, that's like,

832
01:15:56,023 --> 01:16:00,344
[SPEAKER_03]: It takes more to cut one tree than to pay for that.

833
01:16:00,364 --> 01:16:06,226
[SPEAKER_03]: That was like, holy mackerel, that's a, that's pretty.

834
01:16:06,286 --> 01:16:11,008
[SPEAKER_10]: That was really, those are some of the key points that I brought up at that last meeting.

835
01:16:11,028 --> 01:16:23,992
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, I appreciated the commissioner's report, but some of those numbers are just not getting back to, it's what Medford can do, and this ordinance should be for what Medford can do.

836
01:16:24,660 --> 01:16:30,802
[SPEAKER_10]: it's good to look at what's already in place in other cities to help preserve the tree canopy.

837
01:16:31,302 --> 01:16:34,263
[SPEAKER_10]: So, you know, it's hard.

838
01:16:34,303 --> 01:16:40,486
[SPEAKER_10]: They've done all this work already to see what they wrote in the draft and respond to that.

839
01:16:40,826 --> 01:16:42,506
[SPEAKER_10]: But what about the other things they left out?

840
01:16:43,126 --> 01:16:51,970
[SPEAKER_10]: So it's very difficult as far as fees and diameter of breast height.

841
01:16:54,692 --> 01:16:58,174
[SPEAKER_10]: That's all documented in the tree report.

842
01:16:58,214 --> 01:17:05,237
[SPEAKER_10]: If people wanna read that for informational purposes, that's a guide for municipalities to preserve trees.

843
01:17:06,057 --> 01:17:16,963
[SPEAKER_10]: And it will say all the cities that already have an ordinance, the measurements of trees, what they charge anywhere from 100 to $800 per square inch of tree removal.

844
01:17:17,543 --> 01:17:21,645
[SPEAKER_10]: And there have been developers and contractors that actually pay that.

845
01:17:22,510 --> 01:17:25,371
[SPEAKER_10]: And also the aggregate of trees.

846
01:17:25,451 --> 01:17:40,416
[SPEAKER_10]: So if you have a tree that's a foot in diameter, that's 12 inches, and you take out 15 of those, it's the total amount of trees that's calculated in that number of square inch.

847
01:17:42,825 --> 01:17:50,170
[SPEAKER_10]: I will refer to Cambridge and some other cities that do get payments of $200,000 or $400,000 in clear a lot.

848
01:17:50,670 --> 01:17:51,531
[SPEAKER_10]: Does that help us?

849
01:17:51,931 --> 01:17:56,714
[SPEAKER_10]: Where are we going to replace those trees in our lifetime with new trees that may not survive?

850
01:17:56,894 --> 01:18:05,420
[SPEAKER_10]: If you want to read the report, it's on the Go Green website under trees as a guide.

851
01:18:08,010 --> 01:18:10,013
[SPEAKER_10]: That's for educational purposes.

852
01:18:10,153 --> 01:18:24,132
[SPEAKER_10]: If anybody has any questions and they want to email me or Luke, but we're the only two left on the original tree report committee, feel free to email me with questions.

853
01:18:26,880 --> 01:18:35,705
[SPEAKER_03]: I was wondering if the city has the staff to manage an aggressive tree ordinance.

854
01:18:36,465 --> 01:18:41,948
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it was slimmed down to make it simpler to manage.

855
01:18:41,968 --> 01:18:48,852
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't know, Felicia, you know, whether the, since the building

856
01:18:50,184 --> 01:18:53,950
[SPEAKER_03]: The building department would presumably have to issue these permits.

857
01:18:54,051 --> 01:18:56,435
[SPEAKER_03]: They probably wanted to make it so they can manage it.

858
01:18:56,900 --> 01:18:59,160
[SPEAKER_04]: Right, so there's an in-between place, right?

859
01:18:59,240 --> 01:19:02,421
[SPEAKER_04]: So like what they wanted, it was like, can we have some formulas?

860
01:19:03,161 --> 01:19:06,842
[SPEAKER_04]: And if it meets the formula, we charge the money and move on.

861
01:19:07,602 --> 01:19:09,343
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's to help them manage it.

862
01:19:10,003 --> 01:19:16,144
[SPEAKER_04]: But on the other hand, the formula that they're using is too low, right?

863
01:19:16,504 --> 01:19:25,606
[SPEAKER_04]: So if they had literally said the same formula, but they were charging $100,000 an inch or whatever, then everybody would be like, oh, sounds great.

864
01:19:26,647 --> 01:19:40,544
[SPEAKER_04]: So I think that part of what the city council needs to hear is around this feedback that like the thousand dollar number is not the right number, but if they wanted to clear cut a lot, they could pay.

865
01:19:42,382 --> 01:19:58,412
[SPEAKER_04]: $300,000 into the fund, or if they wanted to like for every tree for this many inches it's some number and Laura read has done a ton of research on this, so tell us what number should be, but I think what he was sort of getting at was that.

866
01:19:59,698 --> 01:20:22,774
[SPEAKER_04]: can we do this in a way that somebody doesn't have to go out there and measure every single tree, that we can just issue them a permit and here's how it works, and you make the permit costly enough so people don't just do this lightly, but if they are gonna do it, it generates some real money that can be used for some real stuff, right?

867
01:20:22,794 --> 01:20:25,496
[SPEAKER_04]: I think that's where they were getting at the balance.

868
01:20:28,588 --> 01:20:33,432
[SPEAKER_10]: And what's interesting is they can certainly, like I said, I haven't read the draft.

869
01:20:33,512 --> 01:20:48,223
[SPEAKER_10]: So I don't want to stray too far from what's written or what lawyers may have suggested that have reviewed some of the questions, but how about keeping a percentage of the existing trees, especially if they're a certain size.

870
01:20:49,003 --> 01:20:52,426
[SPEAKER_10]: And I didn't think that was addressed either by the commissioner anyways.

871
01:20:53,267 --> 01:20:56,089
[SPEAKER_10]: So it seemed to me in that committee of the whole meeting,

872
01:20:56,963 --> 01:21:05,995
[SPEAKER_10]: that they were moving towards the lines of allowing completely clear-cutting a lot, no matter what the size or the amount of trees were.

873
01:21:06,896 --> 01:21:09,980
[SPEAKER_10]: So those are things I'll be looking for.

874
01:21:11,442 --> 01:21:14,163
[SPEAKER_04]: To be clear, the city council wasn't moving that way.

875
01:21:14,423 --> 01:21:21,185
[SPEAKER_04]: The building commissioner was recommending it and there was nobody standing there saying, this is a bad idea and here's why.

876
01:21:21,205 --> 01:21:32,289
[SPEAKER_04]: I feel like everybody's super polite at those meetings and nobody wants to contradict the building commissioner and nobody wants to, but so everybody's just like, oh, well, thank you for your recommendation.

877
01:21:32,790 --> 01:21:36,331
[SPEAKER_04]: And what they need is somebody to say, no, here's why.

878
01:21:36,831 --> 01:21:41,593
[SPEAKER_04]: And I don't have the here's why in my head that I can just speak to it like that.

879
01:21:42,174 --> 01:21:45,075
[SPEAKER_04]: Like you have that information in your head.

880
01:21:45,095 --> 01:21:46,035
[SPEAKER_10]: Right.

881
01:21:46,476 --> 01:21:47,236
[SPEAKER_10]: I did speak up.

882
01:21:48,156 --> 01:21:48,496
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes.

883
01:21:49,497 --> 01:22:04,324
[SPEAKER_04]: But what the council's actually doing is making it easy for you to provide them that like, this is a bad idea and here's why in writing so that they can review it without you having to stand up there on TV and do it.

884
01:22:04,938 --> 01:22:06,419
[SPEAKER_10]: Right, right.

885
01:22:06,879 --> 01:22:08,239
[SPEAKER_10]: And Tree's Mansion was there.

886
01:22:08,479 --> 01:22:13,461
[SPEAKER_10]: There were other people that, the only people I think that spoke up was Alicia and myself.

887
01:22:15,002 --> 01:22:19,584
[SPEAKER_10]: So it would have been good if more people had spoken up that are involved in this.

888
01:22:20,704 --> 01:22:27,987
[SPEAKER_10]: But I'm sure Alicia, you'll be watching the calendar in case it comes up, because you might see it first before us.

889
01:22:29,148 --> 01:22:33,949
[SPEAKER_04]: They're likely to say, you know, when, when will the recommendations be back?

890
01:22:33,969 --> 01:22:37,190
[SPEAKER_04]: Do you have recommendations and then base it on that?

891
01:22:37,210 --> 01:22:37,710
[SPEAKER_10]: Okay.

892
01:22:37,730 --> 01:22:38,010
[SPEAKER_10]: All right.

893
01:22:38,650 --> 01:22:42,931
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I think it'll probably be early next year.

894
01:22:44,251 --> 01:22:47,092
[SPEAKER_10]: Well, I'm not going to, I don't want to be surprised.

895
01:22:48,672 --> 01:22:52,293
[SPEAKER_03]: They're going to be going through, there's going to be a whole turnover of people.

896
01:22:52,333 --> 01:22:53,493
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't think they're going to act.

897
01:22:54,410 --> 01:22:57,171
[SPEAKER_03]: before the end of this year, I would say.

898
01:22:57,751 --> 01:22:59,351
[SPEAKER_10]: I do have a question for Alicia.

899
01:22:59,711 --> 01:23:10,114
[SPEAKER_10]: So when years ago, this has been going on for a couple of years, when we had the, I don't know, was it the master plan?

900
